**A LIVE FUNCTIONAL TEST WAS RUN AND PASSED end-to-end** against local
dev servers (real backend, real PubMed API, real frontend, real Zotero
OAuth redirect) per the human's explicit request: searched "Neuroscience,
astrocytes" — got real PubMed results, marked the first 2 Interested,
next 2 Not Interested, confirmed the Saved List showed exactly the 2
Interested papers, then triggered Push to Zotero, which correctly
redirected to the REAL zotero.org login page (with a live Cloudflare
CAPTCHA) — proving the full OAuth wiring is correct end-to-end. Session
stopped there per instructions (completing login needs the human's
real credentials, which nobody should hand to an agent). This wasn't a
one-shot pass — it took 3 rounds of live-testing-driven bug discovery
(see below), each fixed through the full tester/adversarial pipeline.

**Real bugs found ONLY by live testing, never caught by the entire
automated suite (222+ tests) or 15+ prior adversarial reviews:**
1. Backend had NO startup hook to create its DB schema — every test
   used a fixture that manually created tables, so `app.main:app`
   itself had never been booted for real against an empty database
   until this session. A fresh local DB, and the real production Turso
   DB, both 500'd on every request. Fixed with a FastAPI `lifespan`
   calling `SQLModel.metadata.create_all()`.
2. Local SQLite had no concurrency handling — realistic parallel
   frontend requests (a page load's simultaneous fetches) could raise
   `database is locked`. Fixed with WAL mode + busy_timeout, strictly
   gated to the local-only code path (Turso unaffected). Caught a
   `.gitignore` gap along the way (WAL sidecar files weren't ignored).
3. The GitHub Pages-deployed frontend had no way to know the backend
   lives on Render (relative API path would resolve against
   rythdg.github.io itself) — fixed via a VITE_API_BASE_URL build env.
4. Render's Python runtime defaulted to 3.14, which has no prebuilt
   wheel for this project's compiled Turso driver — pinned to 3.12.

**Lesson reinforced, now written down explicitly for whoever resumes:
an entirely green test suite and multiple adversarial review passes
are necessary but NOT sufficient — nothing substitutes for actually
booting the real app and clicking through it as a user would.** Budget
time for this before considering any tier "done," even after full
pipeline sign-off.

**Tier 6**, as literally scoped in BuildPlan.md (lines 687-712), needs
the real deployed system (now closer to ready — see above) plus manual
real-device passes and a real Zotero sandbox login — the login step
specifically needs the human physically present, not something this
orchestrator can ever complete autonomously. Pick this up once the
human has finished the Render env-var setup above.

**Orchestrator process reminder for whoever resumes — READ THE INCIDENT
NOTE FIRST:** every task this build goes through the same pipeline —
specialist implements+tests → `tester` independently verifies (don't
trust the specialist's own COMPLETE entry) → `adversarial-generalist`
reviews (required even when tester found nothing) → orchestrator merges
only once both gate entries exist in their respective build logs →
**commit to git immediately, per task, not batched per tier** → log
here. Fixes found by either gate get sent back to the ORIGINAL
specialist agent via SendMessage (resume, don't respawn) and are
re-verified with the same revert-reproduce-restore rigor before being
accepted — this caught every real bug found this build (see
logs/orchestrator.log for the full blow-by-blow). Don't skip a step
even when a task "looks simple" — Tier 4 alone surfaced 5 real bugs in
tasks that were "just wiring."

**INCIDENT (Tier 4, 2026-07-05):** holding 3 tasks' worth of frontend
work uncommitted while multiple agents ran destructive "revert this,
confirm the test fails, then restore" verification experiments on a
shared, never-committed file (`App.tsx`) let one of those experiments
`git checkout` it back to the oldest commit, silently wiping all of
Tier 4's wiring. Recovered from an agent's own session context, but
this should never be possible again. **Commit each task to git as soon
as tester+adversarial both clear it — do not batch commits across
multiple tasks or wait for a whole tier**, even though this build's
established convention has been one commit per tier for concurrently-
built work. Batch the commit message/log write, not the commit itself.

**Backlog / carried-forward items (none blocking, but don't lose them):**
1. `OAuthSessionBinding` (backend/app/middleware/session.py) has no
   proactive expiry sweep, only lazy expiry-on-resolve — abandoned
   OAuth handshakes accumulate in the single always-on process. Revisit
   at Task 5A (infra) when a natural periodic-task hook exists.
2. Ephemeral `TOKEN_ENCRYPTION_KEY`/`SESSION_COOKIE_SECRET` fallback
   only logs a warning, no environment-aware fail-fast — a real
   deployment booted without these set silently loses encrypted Zotero
   tokens on restart. Revisit at Task 5A when a real deploy environment
   exists to fail-fast against (local dev already has real values set
   in `backend/.env`, so this isn't live today).
3. No unique DB constraint on `(session_id, pmid)` for `QueueDecision`
   despite SPEC §9.2 describing one row per pair. Minor, cheap, still
   open — pick up whenever touching that model next.
4. The credential-in-logs pattern (2 confirmed instances this build:
   NCBI key/email, raw Zotero tokens) has no systemic guard — Task 3D
   considered a repo-wide lint rule against logging raw request/response
   objects and deferred it as heuristic/false-positive-prone. Still
   worth revisiting with a clearer convention if a third instance shows
   up, or before Task 5B's CI is finalized.
5. The new IP-based rate-limiter key (Task 3D) has no reverse-proxy/
   `X-Forwarded-For` awareness — correct for today's direct-to-host
   local dev, but will collapse all real users into one IP bucket if a
   reverse proxy is introduced without trusted-proxy config. Must
   revisit at Task 5A if Render (or similar) sits behind a proxy.
6. No test forces `export.py`'s mid-stream logging wrapper (Task 3D
   fix) to actually fire on a real exception — coverage gap, not a
   correctness gap.
7. (Tier 4) No committed Playwright-level test exercises a Zotero
   mutation while a real browser online/offline event fires — only
   verified via an ad hoc, deleted scratch check when re-verifying the
   `networkMode:"always"` fix. Worth durable coverage if touching
   Zotero+offline again.
8. (Tier 4) `EmptyQueueState.tsx`'s empty-results screen and a couple
   other screens were the LAST to get wired into the shared `ErrorState`
   component — if a new screen needs error/offline copy in a future
   tier, check it's actually using `errorCopy.ts`'s context system
   rather than inventing its own copy, since this happened twice already
   (Task 4C found it once for §5.3a; a second instance may exist
   unflagged in a screen nobody's touched since Tier 2).
9. Local SQLite's connection pool (SQLAlchemy default: 5 + 10
   overflow) will raise `QueuePool timed out` under very high local
   concurrency (dozens of simultaneous writers) — far beyond realistic
   single-user local dev traffic, so not fixed, just documented in
   backend/app/db.py's comments so it isn't confusing if ever hit.
10. `backend/app/main.py`'s `create_all()`-on-boot has two known,
    documented-in-code limitations: an unsynchronized check-then-create
    race under concurrent first boot against a genuinely empty DB
    (harmless today since production tables already exist), and it
    never diffs/migrates columns on an existing table — a future field
    added to an entities.py model needs a real migration, not just a
    redeploy, or this exact bug class recurs one column later.

